library(tidyr)
library(ggplot2)

read_dir <- 'Uncertainty'
fig_dir <- 'figures/'


year_cutoff <- 2040
rms_cutoff <- 0.1

# Figure sizing info
title_size <- 14
axis_size <- 12

read, reshape uncertainty time series

# continue reshaping
uncertainties %>% 
    gather(uncertainty, value, -var, -metric, -rgn, - year) %>%
    distinct->
    uncert_long


uncert_long %>%
    filter(metric == 'full') %>%
    rename(full = value) %>%
    select(-metric) ->
    uncert_full


uncert_long %>%
    filter(metric == 'coef') %>%
    left_join(uncert_full, by = c('year', 'var', 'rgn', 'uncertainty')) ->
    coef_metric

Compare subsets to full

coef_metric %>%
    filter(year >= year_cutoff) %>%
    group_by(rgn, var, metric, uncertainty) %>%
    summarize(rms = sqrt(mean((value-full)^2))) %>%
    ungroup ->
    coef_dist
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'rgn', 'var', 'metric'. You can override
## using the `.groups` argument.
coef_metric %>%
    filter(year >= year_cutoff) %>%
    group_by(rgn,  metric, uncertainty) %>%
    summarize(rms = sqrt(mean((value-full)^2))) %>%
    ungroup ->
    coef_dist2
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'rgn', 'metric'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

identify cutoff, patterns for each metric

ggplot(coef_dist, aes(x = rms, color = interaction(var, uncertainty))) + 
    geom_histogram()+
    facet_wrap(~var) +
    ggtitle('coef')

-spread is tighter for coef (most mass <0.17ish) but proj has fewer outliers for P (more for T)

  • so is 0.2 a fair cutoff for good -> check HS figs

  • if so, then do count > 0.2 for P,T for two coeff

coef below cutoff

coef_dist %>%
    filter(rms >=0.2) %>%
    select(rgn, var) %>%
    distinct %>%
    mutate(id = paste(rgn, var, sep='~')) ->
    coef_bad


coef_dist %>%
    filter(rms <0.2 & rms >= rms_cutoff) %>%
    select(rgn, var) %>%
    distinct  %>%
    mutate(id = paste(rgn, var, sep='~')) ->
    coef_questionable

uncert_long %>%
    mutate(id = paste(rgn, var, sep='~')) %>%
    filter(year >= year_cutoff,
           metric == 'full' | metric == 'coef',
           id %in% coef_bad$id |
               id %in% coef_questionable$id) ->
    coef_rgn_plots

# Order stacks for HS fig
coef_rgn_plots %>%
    mutate(uncertainty = if_else(uncertainty == 'Inter.Annual.Variability', 'A.Inter.Annual.Variability',
                                 if_else(uncertainty == 'Scenario.Uncertainty', 'B.Scenario.Uncertainty',
                                         if_else(uncertainty == 'Model.Uncertainty', 'C.Model.Uncertainty',
                                                 'NA' )))) ->
    coef_rgn_plots

# Extract lines for coef:
coef_rgn_plots %>%
    filter(uncertainty != 'A.Inter.Annual.Variability',
           metric=='coef') %>%
    group_by(year, var, metric, rgn, id) %>%
    summarize(value = sum(value)) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    mutate(uncertainty = 'B.Scenario.Uncertainty') %>%
    bind_rows(coef_rgn_plots %>%
                  filter(uncertainty == 'C.Model.Uncertainty',
                         metric=='coef'))  ->
    coef_rgn_plots2
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year', 'var', 'metric', 'rgn'. You can
## override using the `.groups` argument.
p_tas <- ggplot()+
    geom_bar(coef_rgn_plots %>% filter(metric == 'full', var =='tas'),
             position = 'stack', stat = 'identity',
              mapping=aes(x = year, y = value, color = uncertainty, fill = uncertainty)) +
    scale_color_manual(values = c('darkorange', 'forestgreen', 'blue4')) +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c('darkorange', 'forestgreen', 'blue4')) +
    geom_line(coef_rgn_plots2 %>% filter(var == 'tas'),
              mapping=aes(x = year, y = value, linetype = uncertainty), color = 'white') +
    facet_wrap(~rgn, ncol=6) +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1)) +
    ggtitle('Temperature') +theme_bw() +
     theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
           axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1),
           axis.title = element_text(size = axis_size), 
          plot.title = element_text(size = title_size),
          strip.text = element_text(size = axis_size)) + 
    ylab('fraction of total variance')

ggsave(paste0(fig_dir, 'temperature_HS_regions.png'), p_tas, width = 8, height =6, units = 'in')

Notes

INteresting thing - because our region indices are focused around mid and end of century, our HS figures tend to be closest there.

If we look over 2015 on for comparing metrics instead of 2040, we do see that the latter half of the century is often better than first half even in the bad HS

Differences over regions also interesting - if really care about Russian Arctic or Australia, proj is better. If care about Americas, Africa, Europe, Asia: Coef better.

-> given this is where most agriculture and people are, go with coefficient.
